         <div type="edition"><!-- transcription goes here -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>Decurionum decreto
                    <lb n="2"/>ex domo <persName>
                  <name type="praenomen" key="Lucius">
                     <expan><abbr>L</abbr><ex>uci</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Tarius">Tari</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Rufus">Ruf<hi rend="tall">i</hi>
                  </name>
               </persName>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Agrypnus">Agrypno</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="3"/>medico magistro, ex domo
                    <lb n="4"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Quinta">Quintae</name>
               </persName> matris. <persName>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Agrypnus">Agrypnus</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="5"/>
               <expan><abbr>ann</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> natus <num value="26">XXVI</num> ob<hi rend="tall">i</hi>t septumo
                    <lb n="6"/>vicensumo. Pos<hi rend="tall">i</hi>t mater
                    <lb n="7"/>calimitosa de suo.
                </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>"By decree of the Decurions: For Agrypnus, doctor [and] teacher from the household of Lucius Tarius Rufus [and] from the household of Quinta, his
                    mother. Agrypnus was born 26 years ago and died in the 27th. In her grief, his mother established this with her own money."</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary"><!-- notes go here -->
            <p>Line 1: Lucius Tarius Rufus, infamous Suffect Consul whom Wilson suggests is the L. Tari Rufi of the inscription, was a consul 16 BCE, giving the inscription a late 1st c. BCE or early 1st c. CE provenence.</p>
         </div>
